<div class="ten_section_3">
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				One reason that modernist filmmakers might give as to why the tightly-connected style of Hollywood filmmaking is unpleasant to them is that it doesn’t reflect our experience of the world––particularly the fragmented, random experience of the world that has come to represent modernity. In most Hollywood films, every detail is freighted with meaning and portent that somehow comes into play at some future juncture of the story. But certainly that isn’t how we experience the world. Our lives are filled with insignificant, random details that we encounter and then forget because they play no role in later events. We're used to the idea that people we meet and events that occur will not necessarily hold some kind of significant role in our future lives, that things will not tie up neatly at some point. 
			</p>
			<p>
				If a filmmaker’s personal experience of the world does not fit the mold of a tightly unified series of cause-and-effect events, and yet that filmmaker wants to create a film true to his experience of the world, what options are there? Is it still possible to create a film that coheres on some level?
			</p>
			<p>
				This is the question Harmony Korine wrestles with in this week’s film <em>Gummo</em>. In particular, Korine is rather explicitly attacking the idea of order. Not just order in the real world, but also the way that order is typically found in Hollywood films, a kind of hyper-defined, overly stringent, and predictable order of story structure. 
			</p>
			<p>
				In order to tackle this question of how to represent meaninglessness, I want to include a few paragraphs from the writer Annie Dillard in which she wrestles with exactly this question: what constitutes unity and coherence in artwork that wants to represent a seemingly incoherent world? Or phrased another way: “When is a work ‘about’ meaninglessness, and when is it simply meaningless?” Though Dillard is a writer, and she’s talking about literature, her ideas apply equally well to cinema. 
			</p>
			<p class="quoteIndentation">
				“If the writer's honest intention is to recreate a world he finds meaningless, must his work then be meaningless? If he writes a broken book, is he not then a bad artist? On the other hand, if he unifies a world he sees as shattered, is he not dishonest? All this is an old problem for any writer, for a traditional one as well as a contemporary one. Stated broadly, the question is, What is negative art? What can it be? What can a writer do when his intention is to depict seriously a boring conversation? Must he bore everybody? How should he handle a dull character, a hateful scene? (Everyone knows how the hated voice of a hated character can ruin a book.) Or, in the big time. how can a writer show, as a harmonious, artistic whole, times out of joint, materials clashing, effects without cause, life without depth, and all history without meaning?
			</p>
			<p class="quoteIndentation">
				“. . . . The only real solution is this, which obtains in all art: the writer makes real artistic meaning of meaninglessness the usual way, the old way, by creating a self-relevant artistic whole. He produces a work whose parts cohere. He imposes a strict order upon chaos, And this is what most contemporary modernist fiction does. Art may imitate anything but disorder. The work of art may, like a magician's act, pretend to any degree of spontaneity, randomality, or whimsy, so long as the effect of the whole is calculated and unified. No subject matter whatever prohibits a positive and unified handling . . . . In this structural unity lies integrity, and it is integrity which separates art from nonart.
			</p>
			<p class="quoteIndentation">
				“Let me tread shaky ground in order to insert a note from Rene Magritte on this business of integrity. Any juxtaposition may be startling. Narrative collage is a cheap source of power, An onion ring in a coffin! Paul of Tarsus and Shelly Hack! We can all do this all day. But in the juxtaposition of images, as in other juxtapositions, there is true and false, says Magritte. Magritte says we know birds in a cage. The image gets more interesting if we have, instead of a bird, a fish in the cage, or a shoe in the cage; ‘but though these images are strange they are unhappily accidental, arbitrary. It is possible to obtain a new image which will stand up to examination through having something final, something right about it: it's the image showing an egg in the cage.’
			</p>
			<p class="quoteIndentation">
				“Now, what do we make of this curious assertion of Magritte's, that surrealist images may be right or wrong? What can be right about a surrealist image? I am certainly not going to endorse as an artistic criterion Magritte's vague, emotional phrase ‘something right about it.’ But I do endorse his notion that the right image will ‘stand up to examination.’ After all, there is nothing too mysterious about the rightness of an egg's replacing a bird. The two have met. In other words, the ‘something right’ which ‘will stand up to examination’ is ordinary unity. Notice that Magritte's surrealism by no means intends to traffic in ‘accidental’ or ‘arbitrary’ images. He uses these words to damn. Must arbitrariness always be damning? Must it forever be out of bounds not as a subject but as a technique? I think so.
			</p>
			<p class="quoteIndentation">
				“...In all the arts, coherence in a work means that the relationship among parts--the joined framework of the whole--is actual, solid, nailed down.”
			</p>	
			<p>
				<em>Gummo</em>, by Harmony Korine, is an aggressively nihilistic film that attempts to rebel against the constraints and ideals of traditional narrative structure. It actively violates the majority of traditional rules of narrative and may stretch to the breaking point the definition of what constitutes narrative. However, I’m going to argue that the film itself is not random or meaningless. That, in fact, Korine has replaced the traditional structural components of cause-and-effect with other elements that provide some degree of coherence and unity. (If the above description didn't already clue you in to this fact, let me warn you that <em>Gummo</em> is probably going to be the most challenging film we'll watch this semester. I'm not presenting it as a fun-filled joyride but rather as a good learning opportunity.)
			</p>
			</div>
		</div>
